Today Mr Cameron hit the campaign with Mr Johnson, widely seen as a rival for the Tory leadership.

In an attempt to present a united front, the took on - and beat - youngsters in a game of table football.

Mr Cameron wrote on Twitter: 'Together on the Blue Team. Amazingly, Boris and I managed to win a game of table football at Harrow Skills Centre.'

In a bizarre series of photo opportunities,  the pair also visisted a factory, a building and a market stall, where Mr Cameron said 'Boris [got] his wallet out as we stop for some fruit and veg in Harrow'.

They then travelled back to central London on the Underground together.

The PM was forced to deny being frustrated at Mr Johnson's failure to declare whether he will try to become an MP again at the next election.  

'I don't think it's time for that yet,' Mr Cameron said as he faced repeated questions on the issue as the pair toured a skill centre and met shoppers in north west London.

'Boris has got vital work to do as Mayor of London. All I am saying is that the options are open to him.'

